IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: EFFECTIVE 4/30/2022 THE ORGANIZATION FILED ARTICLES OF DISSOLUTION WITH THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA. THE MISSION OF THE IT GOVERNANCE INSTITUTE (ITGI) IS TO ENHANCE THE EDUCATION OF THE GLOBAL BUSINESS COMMUNITY REGARDING THE GOVERNANCE OF INFORMATION AND INFORMATION SYSTEMS.
IRS990.MissionDesc: EFFECTIVE 4/30/2022 THE ORGANIZATION FILED ARTICLES OF DISSOLUTION WITH THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA. THE IT GOVERNANCE INSTITUTE (ITGI) SHARES WITH ITS AFFILIATED MEMBERSHIP ASSOCIATION, INFORMATION SYSTEMS AUDIT AND CONTROL ASSOCIATION, INC. (ISACA) (RELATED ORGANIZATION), A MISSION OF SERVING PROFESSIONALS AND ORGANIZATIONS BY BEING THE LEADING GLOBAL PROVIDER OF KNOWLEDGE, CERTIFICATIONS, COMMUNITY, ADVOCACY AND EDUCATION ON INFORMATION SYSTEMS ASSURANCE AND SECURITY, GOVERNANCE OF ENTERPRISE INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (IT), AND IT-RELATED RISK AND COMPLIANCE. ITGI'S ROLE FOCUSES ON KNOWLEDGE OF IT GOVERNANCE AND RELATED TOPICS. ITGI SUPPORTS INTERNATIONAL UNDERSTANDING OF GOOD PRACTICES TO DIRECT AND CONTROL AN ENTERPRISE'S IT. THROUGH ITS SUPPORT OF ISACA'S COLLABORATIVE DEVELOPMENT MODEL, ITGI HELPS ENABLE GLOBAL PERSPECTIVE ON CRITICAL ISSUES FACING ENTERPRISE LEADERS AND PRACTITIONERS IN THEIR IT GOVERNANCE RESPONSIBILITIES.
IRS990.Desc: IN 2020 THE ISACA AND ITGI BOARD INITIATED THE PROCESS TO DISSOLVE THE INSTITUTE. THIS PROCESS OF DISSOLUTION CONCLUDED IN APRIL 2022. AS A RESULT, THE ORGANIZATION'S PROGRAM SERVICE ACTIVITIES ARE NO LONGER ACTIVE. THE FOLLOWING DESCRIBES THE ORGANIZATION'S PROGRAM SERVICES PRIOR TO THIS ORGANIZATIONAL CHANGE. IT GOVERNANCE INSTITUTE (ITGI) AND INFORMATION SYSTEMS AUDIT AND CONTROL ASSOCIATION, INC. (ISACA) (RELATED ORGANIZATION) SERVE IT PROFESSIONALS AND ORGANIZATIONS WORLDWIDE THROUGH KNOWLEDGE, CERTIFICATIONS, COMMUNITY, ADVOCACY AND EDUCATION IN THE PROFESSIONAL SPECIALTIES OF THEIR MEMBERS AND ENGAGED PROFESSIONALS. ITGI SUPPORTS ISACA'S WORK TO INCREASE UNDERSTANDING OF THE RELATIONSHIPS AMONG DIFFERENT TYPES OF ENTERPRISE GOVERNANCE AND GLOBAL PRACTICES FOR IMPLEMENTING EFFECTIVE ENTERPRISE GOVERNANCE OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (IT). ITGI FOCUSES PRIMARILY ON FRAMEWORKS AND SUPPORTING DOCUMENTS TO HELP ENTERPRISES ACHIEVE THE FIVE FOCUS AREAS OF IT GOVERNANCE: STRATEGIC ALIGNMENT, PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT, RESOURCE MANAGEMENT, VALUE DELIVERY AND RISK MANAGEMENT

Form990ScheduleAPartVIGrp.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule A, Part IV, Section A, Line 3b Qualified Under 501C(4)(5) Or (6)
Form990ScheduleAPartVIGrp.ExplanationTxt: IT GOVERNANCE INSTITUTE (HEREIN "ITGI") WAS ORGANIZED TO SUPPORT THE PURPOSES OF THE INFORMATION SYSTEMS AUDIT AND CONTROL ASSOCIATION, INC. (HEREIN "ISACA") IN FURTHERANCE OF THEIR VARIOUS CHARITABLE AND EDUCATIONAL PROGRAMS. ISACA IS A WELL-KNOWN PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATION ORGANIZED AND EXEMPT UNDER 501(C)(6) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT IF INSTITUTE WERE AN ORGANIZATION DESCRIBED IN SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE CODE, IT WOULD NOT BE A PRIVATE FOUNDATION BY REASON OF CODE SECTION 509(A)(2). The organization annually confirms the supported organization meets the Section 509(a)(2) public support test. UNDER CODE SECTION 509(A)(3), AN ORGANIZATION MAY BE FORMED TO SUPPORT A 501(c)(6) ORGANIZATION AND ITGI WAS CREATED FOR THIS PURPOSE. ISACA'S PRIMARY EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE IS TO ADVANCE THE INFORMATION SYSTEMS ASSURANCE AND SECURITY PROFESSION. THE SOLE PURPOSE OF ITGI IS TO SUPPORT AND ASSIST IN THE EDUCATIONAL AND OTHER CHARITABLE PURPOSES OF ISACA WHICH ARE DESCRIBED IN SECTION 170(C)(2) OF THE CODE. ITGI IS A MEMBERSHIP ORGANIZATION WITH ISACA AS ITS SOLE MEMBER. AS THE SOLE MEMBER, ISACA ELECTS ALL OF THE FUND'S DIRECTORS. ITGI IS, THEREFORE, CONTROLLED BY ISACA.

Form990ScheduleAPartVIGrp.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule A, Part IV, Section C, Line 1 Majority director detail
Form990ScheduleAPartVIGrp.ExplanationTxt: There is common supervision or control by the persons supervising or controlling both the supporting organization and the supported organization. All (100%) of ITGI's directors also serve as members of the board of directors of ISACA, the supported organization. Additionally, ISACA, the supporting organization, is the sole corporation member of ITGI. As the sole corporate member, ISACA elects all of ITGI's directors and ITGI is therefore controlled by ISACA. These measures are considered to establish the relationship and ensure that the supporting organization is responsive to the needs and requirements of the supported organization.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Schedule J, Part I, Line 3 Arrangement used to establish the top management official's compensation
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: IT Governance Institute's top management officials' compensation is handled by a related organization, Information Systems Audit and Control Association (ISACA). In addition to the ISACA board-approved compensation philosophy, the related organization used the following method to establish the compensation of the organization's CEO/Executive Director: Compensation Committee, independent compensation consultant, Form 990 of other organizations, compensation survey or study and approval by the ISACA Board or Compensation Committee.

ALL REVENUE AND EXPENSES, WHICH INCLUDE EMPLOYEE SALARIES, ARE PROCESSED THROUGH AN INTERCOMPANY ACCOUNT WITH THE INFORMATION SYSTEMS AUDIT AND CONTROL ASSOCIATION, INC. THE PERCENTAGE USED BY ITGI IS NOT MATERIAL TO ISACA.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 12c Conflict of interest policy
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The IT Governance Institute (ITGI) has a conflict of interest policy that defines an interested person (which includes officers, directors, trustees, and key employees) and independent director; directs Board members and others to keep in confidence all ITGI confidential information; requires Board members and others to disclose arrangements that may propose a conflict of interest so that the Conflict of Interest Panel comprised of the Nominating & Governance Committee Chair, Board Chair and ISACA CEO may evaluate such arrangements. This policy details the procedures that must be used in considering a conflict of interest, periodic reviews of any compensation arrangements and other partnerships. Potential conflicts of interest are documented and monitored each year, through (1) self-proclamations made by individual volunteers who sign the participation agreements required for participation in association boards, committees, working groups and task forces; (2) disclosure of conflicts in standard consulting agreements; and (3) disclosure by ISACA employees upon hire (and annually) by review and signature of the organization's employee agreement. Consultants, volunteers and employees are encouraged to report any conflicts that may arise throughout the year. If such instances are reported, they are dealt with at that time and based on the circumstances relating to the potential conflict.
